How to Finance the Green Transition
New York—This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global fight against climate change and submit new commitments to reduce emissions.
The climate crisis is of utmost importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are迟迟 unable to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Luckily, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to combat climate change is increasingly growing.
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Climate Action Special Envoy, CFLI was established with the mission of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy and presents public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the calls from European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to demonstrate greater ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and allocate at least 1 trillion euros for low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed toward climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all of our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects dependent on fossil fuels.
Additionally, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and among the most important issues is climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our resolve.
This summer, European countries have experienced record-breaking high temperatures and poor crop yields due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars every year, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because financing new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing the investment model will be able to accelerate the shift away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
As of 2011, nearly half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States have been retired, while at the same time, the clean energy sector has created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Moreover, an increasing number of U.S. cities and states have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will be supported by the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, which aims to support the full decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As the international community, we must not only invest in clean energy, but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, from the perspective of fossil fuel subsidies, we are effectively spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive the transformation toward a green future.
These investments will yield tremendous returns, including reducing the huge costs of air pollution on public health.
Furthermore, we can take numerous measures to guide the necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors had no knowledge of climate-related risks and did not understand the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather events.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations from the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in a more sustainable manner, and also enabling investors to reward companies that seriously address climate change.
Second, we must clarify investment risks related to green finance.
Cities contribute more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects has been affected.
Government and listed banks must step up their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax benefits have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, helping to overcome intermittency issues more quickly.
Moreover, better grid connectivity can allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to regions experiencing shortages.
Governments can play a leading role in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond at the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
However, compared to the global bond market of $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the ocean.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification system for sustainable finance standards, so that investors can compare similar projects, just as with standard bonds.
Better and more information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment toward low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
